First Shaper tool (hereby named WOOD-E) introductory course has been completed!

![image|666x500](upload://iVutvk7soT5Uq21SRkIm91k04R.jpeg) 

All courtesy of @dsandber who set it up and prepared the [extensive document](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1W1emoI9RWkfNwz3RwGgTy8GorCRj2mbysWKIeWx1sI4/edit?usp=sharing) linked to above. Thanks Dan for taking the time to prepare a great introduction - very informative and to-the-point!

The course was attended by the following members who are all now certified to use the tool:

@MariaEuler 
@bobspeakman 
@NinaLindberg 
@darkturo
@Joannis-Magnus 
@asapienza 
@hampus

@Ollxor is already experienced with the machine from using it the last couple of weeks and is the member together with @dsandber that is most likely able to answer more advanced questions.   

A very useful resource is Shaper's own website https://hub.shapertools.com/ where users from all over the world upload their designs. These are all free to download and use. The growing collection of stuff on there is already impressive ranging from quite complex furniture to simple engravings. Also "meta"-stuff like router tables for woodshops and so on. 

We have an account on the site which is paired with WOOD-E already. This means you simply go to the site, choose a design to download and then you can automagically find it on the Shaper as long as it is within Tau's WiFi range. 

Will update this post (or maybe create a WOOD-E wiki rather) with the login info in the near future (unless someone else makes it happen before me).

